      "comment_id" : 77789060,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "DO NOT DO THIS. Java 7u21 (besides being released in 2013 and thus having missed out on four years of patches big and small) has a arbitrary code execution vulnerability: <a href=\"https://gist.github.com/frohoff/24af7913611f8406eaf3\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">gist.github.com/frohoff/24af7913611f8406eaf3</a>"
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 64856,
        "reputation" : 32443,
        "user_id" : 191246,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 77,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/zRo29.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "ccpizza",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/191246/ccpizza"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1513266517,
      "post_id" : 21705615,
      "comment_id" : 82596166,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "If you installed java via the official .dmg then it should have created a symlink at <code>&#47;Library&#47;Java&#47;Home</code> which will point to the correct <code>JAVA_HOME</code>, therefore a cleaner approach would be adding to your <code>~&#47;.bash_profile</code> something like <code>export JAVA_HOME=&#47;Library&#47;Java&#47;Home</code>. Then after upgrading java you won&#39;t need to update your <code>.bash_profile</code>."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1674364,
